******
[2] Santa Clara County
Date: Fri 8 Sep 2017
Source: San Jose Mercury News [edited]
http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/09/08/two-cases-of-hepatitis-a-linked-to-santa-clara-county-jails/


As other parts of the state contend with a surge in cases of hepatitis A, Santa Clara county officials are investigating how a jail inmate and staff member contracted the disease. The last time a case was reported in the jails was in 2012, said Dr. Sara Cody, the county's health officer. The case involving the inmate was reported to the county Public Health Department at the end of August 2017, and on Tue 5 Sep 2017, the agency received word that a jail staff member also had contracted the disease. Officials would not say in what capacity the staff member worked.

Cody said it wasn't clear whether the cases were connected. "However, because hepatitis A can be spread from person to person, we have really leaned in and are mounting an effort to prevent any further cases through vaccination of staff and inmates," she said.

"The good news about hepatitis A is that it usually just runs its course, and then people are fine," Cody said. The disease is usually spread when a person ingests fecal matter from contact with objects, food or drinks contaminated by feces or stool from an infected person, according to the CDC. It also can be sexually transmitted, usually with men who have sex with men.

Infections can be prevented through careful hand washing and vaccines, the latter of which are being offered to all 3500 inmates and 1800 staff members who work in the jails. "Our 1st concern is to our staff and the population that we care for," Santa Clara County Assistant Sheriff Troy Beliveau said. "We want to make sure that we're giving everybody the proper treatment, the proper tools to prevent this from happening."

Santa Cruz and San Diego counties are both grappling with an outbreak of hepatitis A among their homeless and formerly incarcerated populations, Cody said. "There is no increased risk to the public at large," Cody said about the Santa Clara County cases. "This is confined to the jail setting."

